{
  "texts": [
    "I. INTRODUCTIONDistributed databases power mission-critical services such as financial applications, e-commerce platforms, logistics systems, and global-scale social networks.",
    "Their performance and availability depend on the ability to scale elastically in response to changing workloads.",
    "However, while elasticity is widely advertised as a core feature of cloud-native data systems, the mechanisms and assumptions behind autoscaling remain simplistic and are often suboptimal in practice.",
    "Limitations of the Binary Scaling ParadigmModern databases expose two principal scaling dimensions: 1) Horizontal scaling (scale-out): add or remove nodes.2) Vertical scaling (scale-up): increase or decrease pernode CPU, RAM, storage IOPS, or network bandwidth.Nearly all real-world systems-including Spanner [6], Dy-namoDB [7], Bigtable [3], Cassandra [11], CockroachDB [4], and YugabyteDB [12]-treat these two scaling axes as independent, leaving operators and cloud controllers to choose between scale-out or scale-up based on limited heuristics.",
    "This dichotomy is problematic."
  ]
}